# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-bausch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:edward-bausch/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:edward-bausch/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:edward-bausch/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:edward-bausch/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:edward-bausch/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:edward-bausch/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:edward-bausch/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:edward-bausch/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Bausch + Lomb was a public company listed on the NYSE, until it was acquired by private equity firm Warburg Pincus in 2007.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In May 2013, Canadian-based Valeant Pharmaceuticals announced that it would acquire Bausch + Lomb from Warburg Pincus for $4.5 billion in cash.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The deal, which was approved by shareholders, closed on August 5, 2013.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] On May 6, 2022, the company completed an initial public offering and again became publicly traded.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] As of 2022, the company employs about 12,900 people, and manufactures and markets health care products directly or indirectly in approximately 100 countries.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1853, John Bausch and Henry Lomb, both German immigrants, established a small but ambitious workshop producing monocles in Rochester, New York.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] By 1861, their operation had expanded to manufacturing vulcanite rubber eyeglass frames and other precision vision products.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] During the American Civil War, the Union blockade caused the price of gold and European horn to rise dramatically.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] This resulted in a growing demand for the Bausch + Lomb spectacles made from vulcanite.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1876, Ernst Gundlach joined the company as it began to manufacture microscopes.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Later that year, the Bausch & Lomb Optical Company won a distinction at the Philadelphia Centennial Exposition.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The company also produced photographic lenses (1883), spectacle lenses (1889), microtomes (1890), binoculars and telescopes (1893).
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] From 1892 in cooperation with Zeiss in Germany, the company produced optical lenses.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In this manner, at the end of the 19th century, the product range included eyeglasses, microscopes and binoculars, as well as projectors, camera lenses and camera diaphragms.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] With the growth of the US army, under President Theodore Roosevelt and the buildup of the naval fleet, Bausch & Lomb received the commission, through the supplier Saegmuller, to manufacture high-precision lenses for optical measurement and founded a joint venture with Saegmuller.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] At the same time as this new expansion, a research department with five members was started to develop new products and improve old ones.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] A new alliance with the Zeiss company in Germany ensured competitive advantages for the three participants, Bausch & Lomb, Saegmuller and Zeiss, in terms of patent use and opening new markets.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1902, William Bausch, the son of the founder, developed a process to create the desired lens shape directly by casting molten glass.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Previously, the glass parts for the lenses had to be separated, ground and polished in a complicated process, and this brought significant savings in time and materials.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The company produced the first optical-quality glass in America during the early to mid-1900s.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] By the year 1903 the company began manufacturing microscopes, binoculars, and camera shutters.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The further development of the firm was affected by political events.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Because of the World Wars and the consequent need for optical instruments such as field glasses, range finders, camera lenses, binocular telescopes, searchlight mirrors, torpedo tube sights, and periscopes, the product range could be considerably broadened.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Until World War I, optical glass and the instruments made from it (including many military instruments) were often imported into most European and North American countries from Germany.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The same was also true of chemical products and laboratory equipment.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The outbreak of the war, with Germany's new enemy status, created a scramble to rapidly enhance the domestic industries.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1933, Bausch + Lomb started to honor outstanding high school science students with the Bausch+Lomb Honorary Science Award.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In the 1930s, military products represented 70% of total production.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The Ray-Ban brand of sunglasses was developed for pilots in 1936.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] At a time when the cinema was being superseded by television, Bausch & Lomb developed improved optics for the CinemaScope process, which popularized the film-based anamorphic format and led most cinemas to double the widths of their screens.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1965 Bausch & Lomb acquired the patent for the hydrogel contact lenses created by Czech scientists Otto Wichterle and Drahoslav Lím.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1971, after three years of development work, two years for the medical approval by the United States Food and Drug Administration and an investment of three million USD, Bausch + Lomb launched contact lenses made of Poly-HEMA.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In contrast to the contact lenses previously available, made of glass and Lucite (acrylic glass), the new lenses were softer.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] They were marketed under the brand name "Soflens".
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In the 1970s, the company was a major producer of spectrophotometers for the dye and chemical business, such as the Spectronic 20.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] A massive restructuring of the company began in the mid-1980s.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] What had been the core divisions, the production of lenses for various purposes, were sold off.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The sunglasses division was continued as Ray-Ban and kept selling well due to effective product placement.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] By the planned acquisition of other firms, such as Polymer Technology Corporation and Dr.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Mann Pharma, existing business areas such as contact lens production were strengthened and new ones were initiated.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1997, as a result of a series of company acquisitions, the division for the manufacture of surgical products was established.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The Ray-Ban brand was sold in 1999 to the Italian Luxottica Group.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Since then, Bausch & Lomb has developed into a globally operating company which is one of the largest producers of contact lenses.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] As of 2022, about 12,900 employees in approximately 100 countries work for the firm.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Competitors in the international eye care products market are Johnson & Johnson, Allergan, Alcon, MSD-Chibret, CooperVision, Menicon Co., Hoya Corporation, EssilorLuxottica and Carl Zeiss Meditec.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 2023, Bausch + Lomb Corp announced it would buy Xiidra from Novartis for $1.75 billion and pay additional $750 million in linked to future sales for Xiidra as well as two pipeline asset.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 2025, Bausch + Lomb's subsidiaries closed an offering of $790.6 million.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In the last few years, several business areas in the Vision Care division have been developed in the framework of product diversification.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The vision care segment is its main business activity, making up 58% of their quarter one 2025 revenue leading with the manufacturing of contact lenses.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The product assortment includes daily soft contact lens that are designed to be worn and discarded at the end of the day, such as the "Biotrue ONEday" or "Bausch + Lomb ULTRA" silicone hydrogel lenses which can be changed after seven days without being taken out at night.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] These newer lens ranges represent advancements in material science and design, offering enhanced comfort, moisture retention, and visual clarity for a variety of patients including those with astigmatism or presbyopia.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Additionally, Bausch + Lomb manufactures lens-care products including disinfectant solutions, eye drops and eye vitamins.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] For contact lens users, the company provides cleaning, disinfectant and rinsing solutions as well as rewetting drops.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] They have recently focused on expending their eye drops for individuals with dry eye symptoms, eye allergies or eye redness with products such as Lumify eye drops, launching in 2018, and Blink for dry eye relief.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The entire Blink portfolio was acquired from Johnson & Johnson in 2023.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Lumify is the only redness reliever that's a selective alpha-2 AR agonist recommended by doctors for avoiding activity on the alpha-1 receptor which is associated with rebound redness.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Their eye vitamins and supplements portfolio includes various formulations aimed at addressing overall eye health, dry eye symptoms and macular health and reducing the risk of progression of Age-related Macular Degeneration (AMD).
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] This began with the launch of PreserVision in 2001 following their collaboration with the National Eye Institute on an AREDS study.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] It grew in 2013 when Ocuvite eye vitamins to support eye health was launched.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The portfolio expanded recently with the launch of Blink NutriTears in 2024 intended to support tear film health.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 2026, Bausch + Lomb released a new version of the AREDS2 formula, PreserVision AREDS3.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The Pharmaceuticals division manufactures pharmaceutical eye products, which accounted for about 26% of their 2025 quarter one revenue.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] This segment consists of prescription medicines for post-operative treatments and treatments for a number of eye conditions such as glaucoma, eye inflammation, ocular hypertension, dry eyes and retinal diseases.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The company's engagement with specific dry eye disease treatments has developed in recent years launching Miebo in 2023 after receiving U.S.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approval in May and acquiring Xiidra from Norvartis in September of that year.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] These prescription medications target different aspects of dry eye disease, with Miebo addressing tear evaporation and Xiidra focusing on inflammation.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The Surgicals division provides medical device equipment, consumables, and instrumental tools and technologies for the treatment of corneal, cataract, vitreous and retinal eye conditions.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] This includes interocular lenses and delivery systems, phacoemulsification equipment, and other surgical instruments and devices necessary for cataract surgery.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] On July 2, 2004, the company announced that it had licensed the intellectual property of Novartis.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Bausch & Lomb will pay the Ciba Vision unit of Novartis a royalty on net U.S. sales of its PureVision brand contact lenses until 2014 and on net sales outside the U.S. until 2016.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] But as of now, the brand FreshLook comes under Bausch and Lomb and Ciba manufacturers it.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1994, several states in the US, including Texas, opened an investigation against Bausch & Lomb.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] This investigation was based on the sale of duplicate contact lenses under different names and prices.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Three different versions of the same contact lens were being sold under OptimaFW, Medalist lenses, and SeeQuence2.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] OptimaFW, the most expensive version, was available with a lifetime of one year, The mid-priced, Medalist lenses were sold with a lifetime of three months, and SeeQuence2, the least expensive, came with a lifetime of two to three weeks.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] By 1996, the company ensured that all three versions carried the OptimaFW tag and tried to standardize the packaging, but the pricing was still different.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1996, the case was settled for $68 million.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 1997, 17 states pressured Bausch & Lomb to stop the sale of duplicate lenses, deceptive practice stated in the court.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The settlement also demanded the company to pay $1.7 million or $100,000 to each state to cover investigative costs.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 2009, Bausch & Lomb spent $250 million to settle six hundred lawsuits filed by consumers exposed to *Fusarium* keratitis, a fungal infection, after using its contact solution ReNu with MoistureLoc.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Between June 2005 and September 2006, one hundred eighty cases were reported, out of which seven patients required eye removal and sixty required corneal transplants.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Bausch + Lomb was involved in a lawsuit with Novartis, which claimed to have patents on a Bausch + Lomb product called PureVision.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] On June 26, 2002, a federal judge ruled that Bausch & Lomb did infringe on Ciba Vision (a subsidiary of Alcon) patents.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] On April 11, 2006, Bausch & Lomb stopped shipments of its ReNu with MoistureLoc contact lens solution when the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) announced there was a high correlation between use of the product and cases of suspected fungal keratitis.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] The Centers for Disease Control found that "nearly all of the company's ReNu with MoistureLoc eye care products were linked to severe fungal eye infections".
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] Two class action lawsuits were filed against Bausch & Lomb in relation to the eye fungus problems.
[src:edward-bausch/bausch-lomb] In 2003, Bausch & Lomb received a 100% rating on the Corporate Equality Index released by the Human Rights Campaign.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky was born in New York City on March 8, 1925, to Russian immigrant parents, Louis and Rose (Chaplick) Budiansky.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] Upon obtaining a Bachelor of Civil Engineering degree from City College of New York in 1944 when he was barely over 19, he became an aeronautical research scientist at the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA, forerunner to NASA) at Langley Field, Virginia.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He took an educational leave from NACA to enroll in 1947 in the graduate program in applied mathematics at Brown University, completing his Ph.D. in 1950 with a dissertation entitled *Fundamental Theorems and Consequences of the Slip Theory of Plasticity*.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He returned to Langley in 1950 and, in 1952, was appointed Head of the Structural Mechanics Branch.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He joined the faculty of Harvard in 1955.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He made widely cited contributions on the way that fissures and joints in rocks affect the propagation of seismic waves, which has become a standard basis for inferring rock properties in the Earth, and contributed to understanding stressing and deformation in the inflation of the human lung.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] His work of the later years was focused on problems in the domain of materials science, explaining mechanical properties of solids in terms of microscopic mechanisms.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He referred to this important area as "micromechanics".
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He was one of its pioneers, and contributed to explanation of the fracture of ductile metals and the toughening of normally brittle ceramics and composite materials.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky won many honors including the AIAA 1970 Dryden Research Lecturer; CCNY 1974 Townsend Harris Medal; ASCE 1982 von Karman Medal; Society of Engineering Science 1985 Eringen Medal; ASME 1989 Timoshenko Medal.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He received honorary doctorates from Northwestern University 1986 and Technion Israel Institute of Technology.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] In addition he was a member of the National Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Engineering, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences; the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences; and the Danish Center for Applied Mathematics and Mechanics.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] Professional affiliations included: ASCE, ASME, AIAA, and AGU.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] Bernard Budiansky died January 23, 1999, at his home in Lexington, Massachusetts, aged 73.
[src:edward-bausch/bernard-budiansky] He was survived by his wife and two sons, one of whom is writer Stephen Budiansky.
[src:edward-bausch/edward-bausch] Bausch was born in Rochester, New York to John Jacob Bausch and Barbara (Zimmermann) Bausch.
[src:edward-bausch/edward-bausch] He obtained his engineering degree from Cornell University in 1874.
[src:edward-bausch/edward-bausch] He was a brother of Delta Kappa Epsilon.
